Package com.telenav.mesakit.graph

Class GraphElement

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.mesakit.graph.GraphElement
All Implemented Interfaces:

Direct Known Subclasses:
Edge, EdgeRelation, GraphNode, Place
public abstract class GraphElement extends Object implements com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.naming.Named, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.collection.Indexed, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.collection.LongKeyed, com.telenav.kivakit.validation.Validatable, com.telenav.kivakit.core.string.AsIndentedString
Base class for Edge, EdgeRelation, Vertex, ShapePoint and Place elements in a Graph. This abstraction allows them to be treated the same when they are, for example, stored in a spatial index. It also allows for a common data indexing scheme and storage of common attributes.

Graph elements have a Graph and a GraphElementIdentifier subclass that can be retrieved with identifier(). An Edge has an EdgeIdentifier, a vertex has a VertexIdentifier and so on. This identifier can also be retrieved as a long value when the situation warrants it. Graph elements also have a MapIdentifier subclass retrieved by mapIdentifier() that relates to the entity they were derived from in the source data. For example, Edges are associated with PbfWayIdentifiers, Vertexes are associated with PbfNodeIdentifiers and so on.

Identifiers

  • identifier()
  • identifierAsLong()
  • mapIdentifier()

A graph element conforms to the owning graph's DataSpecification and has various Attributes. The attributes supported by a graph element can be retrieved with attributes(), and whether an element supports a particular attribute can be determined with supports(Attribute).

Attributes

  • attributes()
  • supports(Attribute)

Every element in a graph supports tagging with key / value pairs. These tags can be retrieved with:

Tags

  • tag(String)
  • tagList()
  • tagMap()
  • tagValue(String)
  • hasTag(String)

Graph elements have a bounds() and the method isInside(Rectangle), determines if the element is fully contained in the given rectangle.

Elements also have a variety of metadata attributes, which are common to all DataSpecifications.:

Metadata

  • metadata()
  • dataSpecification()
  • lastModificationTime()
  • pbfChangeSetIdentifier()
  • pbfRevisionNumber()
  • pbfUserIdentifier()
  • pbfUserName()

Graph elements are tiny objects, and mostly have only three fields:

  • 1. graph - A reference to the Graph that contains the element
  • 2. identifier - A GraphElementIdentifier used to identify the element in the graph
  • 3. index - An index used to access element attributes the GraphElementStore for the type of element
The small size of graph elements (and most subclasses do not add any fields) makes it very fast to allocate new elements (particularly with modern generational garbage collectors). This design pattern is known as "flyweight", which gives the name "heavyweight" to graph elements that don't make use of this pattern but instead store all their attributes in fields (HeavyWeightEdge, HeavyWeightVertex, HeavyWeightRelation and HeavyWeightPlace). Heavyweight graph elements are inefficient to construct relative to flyweight elements and are used only temporarily during graph loading as well as in testing.

Graph elements support the hashCode() / equals(Object) contract and are Validatable. Subclasses override the Validatable.validator(ValidationType) method to provide validation before elements are saved to a GraphArchive and before a GraphLoader adds them to a GraphElementStore. To allow elements to be treated the same as many other objects that are Quantizable to a long value (in this case the identifier), GraphElement implements quantum().
